<bill id="DLM3335202" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" xml:lang="en-NZ" year.imprint="2010" bill.no="231" bill.type="government" stage="1" year="2010">
  <billdetail>
    <title>Nga Wai o Maniapoto (Waipa River) Bill</title>
    <billtype>Government Bill</billtype>
    <explnote id="DLM3335203" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" rule-after="yes" rule-before="yes" bill.no="231" bill.type="government" stage="1" year="2010">
      <heading>Explanatory note</heading>
      <explnote.group>
        <heading>General policy statement</heading>
        <para>
          <text>This Bill gives effect to a deed entered into between the Crown and Maniapoto by which the Crown and Maniapoto agree to—</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>extend a co-governance framework over the whole of the Waipa River and provide for Maniapoto to participate in the framework; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>establish co-management and related arrangements with Maniapoto in relation to the Waipa River.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <explnote.crosshead>Scope of deed</explnote.crosshead>
        <para>
          <text>The co-governance framework for the Waipa River—</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>is an extension of the co-governance framework for the Waikato River from Te Taheke Hukahuka to the mouth of the river (Te Puaha o Waikato), including the Waipa River from its junction with the Puniu River to its junction with the Waikato River at Ngaruawahia; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>includes the Waipa River from its source at Pekepeke Spring to its junction with the Puniu River.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The co-governance framework is extended to the Waipa River from its source at Pekepeke Spring to its junction with the Puniu River to set the direction for achieving the overarching purpose of the deed, which is to restore and maintain the quality and integrity of the waters that flow into and form part of the Waipa River for present and future generations and the care and protection of the mana tuku iho o Waiwaia.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>In the overarching purpose—</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>the phrase <quote.in quote="1">the waters that flow into and form part of the Waipa River</quote.in> refers to the connected and flowing body of water that comprises the Waipa River together with all its associated waters and water columns, including those flowing through its floodplains and the Maniapoto karst, streams, waterways, tributaries, springs, geothermal springs, watercourses, and lakes but does not include any unconnected waters or artificial watercourse such as an irrigation canal, water supply race, canal for the supply of water for electricity power generation, or farm drainage canal;</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>reference to <quote.in quote="1">the mana tuku iho o Waiwaia</quote.in> means the ancestral authority and prestige handed down from generation to generation in respect of Waiwaia, as described in the deed in statements of significance; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text><quote.in quote="1">Waiwaia</quote.in> refers to the essence and wellbeing of the Waipa River (to Maniapoto Waiwaia is the personification of the waters of the Waipa River and its ancient and enduring spiritual guardian).</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The extended co-governance framework recognises the distinct interests of Maniapoto in the Upper Waipa River and the interests of Maniapoto in the Lower Waipa River where Waikato-Tainui also have interests, complementing arrangements agreed between the Crown and Waikato-Tainui in a deed of settlement signed on 17 December 2009 and in separate deeds between the Crown and the iwi whose interests are in the Upper Waikato River, namely Ngati Tuwharetoa, Raukawa and Te Arawa River Iwi.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The co-management arrangements with Maniapoto relate to the interests of Maniapoto in the whole of the Waipa River. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The policy objectives associated with the co-governance framework and the co-management arrangements are to—</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>provide legal mechanisms for Maniapoto to participate in the governance and management of the Waipa River given the acknowledged significance of the Waipa River to Maniapoto;</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>recognise that the Crown has a responsibility, in terms of the principles of the Treaty of Waitangi, to provide for the relationship of Maniapoto and their culture and traditions with the Waipa River;</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>streamline, improve and co-ordinate governance and management arrangements for the Waipa River and the Waikato River to support their strategic importance to New Zealand’s social, cultural, environmental and economic wellbeing; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>provide clear direction and certainty about the co-governance and co-management of the Waipa River.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The deed between the Crown and Maniapoto does not settle any historical Treaty of Waitangi claims of Maniapoto relating to the Waipa River.</text>
        </para>
        <explnote.crosshead>Background</explnote.crosshead>
        <para>
          <text>Maniapoto is an iwi of the Tainui waka with more than 33,600 members of whom more than 11,000 reside within the Manaipoto rohe.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The relationship between the people of Maniapoto and the Waipa River is historic, intellectual, physical and spiritual.  Historically, te mana o te wai was such that it provided all manner of sustenance to Maniapoto including physical and spiritual nourishment that has, over generations, maintained the quality and integrity of Maniapoto marae, whanau, hapu and iwi.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Waipa River is a taonga to Maniapoto.  To the people of Maniapoto, their relationship with the Waipa River and their respect for it lies at the heart of their spiritual and physical wellbeing, and their tribal identity and culture and the particular characteristics of the Upper Waipa River and its place within the rohe and customs of Maniapoto is of special significance to Maniapoto.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Waipa River is a significant contributor to social, cultural, environmental and economic wellbeing within its region.  The Waipa River is also a significant contributor to the waters of the Lower Waikato River.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The restoration and maintenance of the Waipa River, as part of a larger catchment, needs to be coordinated with the management of the Waikato River and will have a major impact on the effectiveness of the Vision and Strategy, and other arrangements to restore and protect the health and wellbeing of the Waikato River.  This whole of river approach is consistent with the desire of Maniapoto to keep intact the mauri of the Waipa River in its entirety.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Crown and Maniapoto consider that Maniapoto involvement in a new era of co-governance and co-management in respect of the Waipa River is a key factor in achieving the longer-term sustainability of the quality and integrity of the waters that flow into and form part of the Waipa River for present and future generations and the care and protection of the mana tuku iho o Waiwaia.</text>
        </para>
        <explnote.crosshead>Summary of co-governance framework</explnote.crosshead>
        <para>
          <text>The Crown and Maniapoto share a commitment to work together in a co-governance framework to set the primary direction to achieve the overarching purpose of the deed.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The co-governance framework comprises—</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>recognition of the specific and enduring relationship of Maniapoto with the Waipa River;</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>development of objectives for the Waipa River by Maniapoto;</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>legislative recognition of the vision and strategy extending over the whole of the Waipa River, including the ability to amend the vision and strategy to achieve the overarching purpose of the deed insofar as the vision and strategy relates to the Upper Waipa River;</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>granting functions and powers to the Waikato River Authority through legislation in respect of the Upper Waipa River; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>clean-up arrangements for the Upper Waipa River.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill provides a legislative basis for the vision and strategy to apply to the Upper Waipa River (from its source at Pekepeke Spring to its junction with the Puniu River) and activities in its catchment that affect the Upper Waipa River.  The Bill also provides for reviews of the vision and strategy to include consideration of the Upper Waipa River within the context of the overarching purpose of the deed.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Under the Waikato-Tainui Raupatu Claims (Waikato River) Act 2010, the vision and strategy has been incorporated directly into the Waikato regional policy statement and is a statement of general policy under conservation legislation.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill provides that the functions and jurisdiction of the Waikato River Authority are extended to the Upper Waipa River and the basis upon which the functions will be carried out in respect of the Upper Waipa River.</text>
        </para>
        <explnote.crosshead>Summary of co-management arrangements</explnote.crosshead>
        <para>
          <text>The Crown and Maniapoto share a commitment to enter a new era of co-management over the Waipa River.  The successful implementation of co-management requires a new approach to relationships the Crown, relevant local authorities and agencies have with Maniapoto.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The co-management arrangements include—</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>establishment of joint management agreements with relevant local authorities;</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>an Upper Waipa River integrated management plan;</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>recognition of the Maniapoto iwi environmental management plan;</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>regulations relating to fishing;</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>power for regulations to be made for the management of aquatic life, habitats and natural resources managed under conservation legislation;</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>Crown facilitated discussions between Maniapoto and relevant local authorities and agencies with a view to providing exemptions for customary activities; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>relationship mechanisms including the Waiwaia Accord, accords between Ministers and Maniapoto and a relationship forum.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill establishes a new form of joint management agreement and requires relevant local authorities to put joint management agreements in place with Maniapoto covering the following functions, powers and duties under the Resource Management Act 1991—</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>monitoring and enforcement relating to the Waipa River and activities within its catchment affecting the Waipa River;</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>preparing, reviewing, changing or varying Resource Management Act 1991 planning documents to the extent that those processes relate to the vision and strategy; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>the processing, but not decision making, steps with regard to specified applications for resource consent relating to the Waipa River.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill prescribes the process for Maniapoto, relevant Ministers and the Waikato Regional Council to prepare and approve and integrated management plan for the Upper Waipa River and establishes the legal effect of the plan.  The components of the Upper Waipa River integrated management plan are—</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>a conservation component which has the status of a conservation management plan and a freshwater fisheries management plan under the Conservation Act 1987;</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>a fisheries component which has the status of a fisheries plan under the Fisheries Act 1996;</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>a regional council component which a relevant local authority must have regard to when preparing, reviewing or changing a Resource Management Act 1991 planning document; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>any other component that may be agreed in future between iwi and any appropriate agency, including a local authority, responsible for administering enactments that affect the Waipa River and activities in its catchment that affect the Waipa River, or carrying out functions or exercising powers under enactments that affect the Waipa River.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Local authorities preparing, reviewing or changing a Resource Management Act 1991 planning document must recognise the Maniapoto iwi environmental management plan in the same manner as would be required under the Resource Management Act 1991 for any document recognised by an iwi authority.  A consent authority must have regard to the Maniapoto iwi environmental management plan if the consent authority considers section 104(1)(c) of the Resource Management Act 1991 applies to the plan.  Persons carrying out duties under sections 12 to 14 of the Fisheries Act 1996 must recognise and provide for the Maniapoto iwi environmental management plan to the extent its contents relate to those functions, powers and duties.  Persons exercising functions, powers or duties under the conservation legislation in relation to the Waipa River and its catchment must have particular regard to the Maniapoto iwi environmental management plan to the extent its contents relate to the exercise of those functions, powers and duties.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill requires regulations to be made under the Fisheries Act 1996 to provide for Maniapoto to—</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>manage customary fishing in the Waipa River catchment through the issuing of customary fishing authorisations; and</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>recommend to the Minister of Fisheries the making of bylaws restricting or prohibiting fishing on the Waipa River, which will be made unless the Minister of Fisheries considers that an undue adverse effect on fishing would result.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill establishes a power to make regulations for the Upper Waipa River for the management of aquatic life, habitats, and natural resources managed under conservation legislation consistent with the overarching purpose.</text>
        </para>
      </explnote.group>
      <explnote.group>
        <heading>Regulatory impact statement</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Office of Treaty Settlements in the Ministry of Justice produced a regulatory impact statement to help inform the main policy decisions taken by the government relating to the content of this Bill.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>A copy of the regulatory impact statement can be found at the following web pages:</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>
                  <citation jurisdiction="nz">
                    <extref href="http://nz01.terabyte.co.nz/ots/DocumentLibrary/RegulatoryImpactStatementUpperWaipaRiver.pdf">http://nz01.terabyte.co.nz/ots/DocumentLibrary/RegulatoryImpactStatementUpperWaipaRiver.pdf</extref>
                  </citation>
                </text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
